 inner conflicts, paradoxes, and greed at the heart of land-use disputes from the back rooms of Washington to the grassroots efforts of passionate citizens. Into this mix, Trimble weaves the personal story of how he, a lifelong environmentalist, ironically became a landowner and developer himself, and began to explore the ethics of ownership anew. We travel with Trimble in a fascinating journey that becomes, in the end, a hopeful credo to guide citizens and communities seeking to reinvent their relationship with the beloved American landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLand usezWest (U.S.). 0aReal estate developmentzWest (U.S.). 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  a2002 olympics.  aacademic.  aamerican history.  aamerican west.  aathletes.  abillionaires.  aenvironmentalist.  aethics.  agrassroots.  aland developer.  anorthern utah.  aolympian.  aolympic skier.  aolympics.  aphotographer.  aregional.  asalt lake city olympics.  asalt lake city.  ascholarly.  aski resort.  askiing.  asnow.  aunited states history.  aus history.  autah.  awestern states.  awestern united states.  awestern world.  awinter sports.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025111340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093373640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520933736423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520933736/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY